Yeah, before I was heavily into automation (i.e. puppet) this was my go to command. Use a for loop and ssh to run things on a group of systems.<p><pre><code>  for host in h-abc h-def h-ghi h-jkl h-mno h-pqr h-stu h-vwx h-yza; 
    do 
    ssh -l root $host &quot;hostname; echo &quot;1.1.1.1 server&quot; >> /etc/hosts&quot;; 
  done
</code></pre>
This would iterate over hosts (h-abc .. h-yza) and run the commands &quot;hostname; echo &quot;1.1.1.1 server&quot; >> /etc/hosts&quot;. Or maybe use a for loop and scp to push the files out and then run md5 to verify they are correct. It was a hack but useful for a small set of machines.<p>ps. if you are interested in learning about puppet, I have put together a screencast about it @ <a href="http://sysadmincasts.com/episodes/8-learning-puppet-with-vagrant" rel="nofollow">http://sysadmincasts.com/episodes/8-learning-puppet-with-vag...</a>
